With your permission, Mr. Speaker, and the consent of the House, I should like to answer Questions Nos. 90 and 92.

Having regard to the great importance of developing the tourist traffic to the fullest extent possible consistently with the need for protecting the conditions of the workers and the building up of an efficient labour force, I have decided, after consultation with the two sides of the industry, to direct the Catering Wages Commission to inquire into the operation of the Catering Wages Act in the hotel industry in relation to the means for meeting the requirements of the public, including in particular the requirements of visitors from overseas, both generally


and with special reference to the following questions:


(i) whether there is sufficient flexibility in its operation
(a) as a matter of normal practice;
(b) at holiday times;

(ii) whether special arrangements are necessary to deal with the problems of seasonal hotels and hotels in rural areas including hotels in Scotland;

(iii) whether it is practicable and desirable to simplify the existing arrangements;

(iv) whether in the light of experience under the Act any change in principle as regards taking tips into account as a factor affecting statutory minimum remuneration is necessary or desirable.
I propose to appoint as assessors, to be available to the Commission in connection with this inquiry, persons drawn from the two sides of the industry, including one from Scotland. The Commission have informed me that amongst the bodies they will consult will be the British Tourist and Holidays Board, the Scottish Tourist Board and the Welsh Tourist Board. I have asked the Commission to deal with the inquiry as a matter of urgency.
